<br>
Yes, you should &quot;sit and listen&quot;.  Otherwise, you make yourself look ignorant when you attempt to refute arguments people with differing opinions are expressing.  Plugging your ears with your forefingers and singing &quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>La la la la la la la!  I can't hear you!  La la la la la la la!  I'm not listening!</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot; only makes you look childish.<br>
<br>
This isn't to say that one must accept every argument.  Far from that.  But if you want to understand what someone else is saying beyond the most superficial level, then yes, you should &quot;sit and listen&quot;.  You should also do your best not to mischaracterise the other position.  Mischaracterising the other side lets the slip show in your argument--the ideology beneath the argument, for those who are attuned to that kind of thing.<br>
<br>
Of course, Americans are badly trained in how to argue.  Shouting matches on CNN's Crossfire are considered &quot;intellectual debate&quot; and he with the catchiest, and pithiest, sound-byte wins. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~andersonrob/LASLAN.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=madrain>madrain</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>High Priest of Rerolli Marr</span><br>  Posts: 1265<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(2/19/03 1:36:37 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=11.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: God and America</span><hr size=1> A-hahaha!  This sucks horrendously.<br>
