<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Of course, Americans are badly trained in how to argue. Shouting matches on CNN's Crossfire are considered &quot;intellectual debate&quot; and he with the catchiest, and pithiest, sound-byte wins.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
Agreed.  How often do you see these guys admit that the other might have made a good point?  Very rarely.  It's almost a sign of weakness to say that.  When did that happen in this country?  <br>
<br>
Have we become so damn competitive about everything that we refuse to acknowledge someone else's argument?  Shouldn't a good debate also be a learning experience?  Most of the posters on this board are obviously intelligent, compassionate people - so why would you want to rip them personally - because you don't agree with them on one topic?<br>
<br>
Sorry for the rambling that is going to follow, but I'm a bit grouchy this morning.  I was thinking last night about how competitive Americans are and how it ties in to public opinion and our foreign policy.  Are we really going after Iraq as a supporter of terrorism, or are we just still pissed off that some terrorists got over on us on 9/11?  If that is the case, how long will it take us to make us feel like we have gotten our revenge + 5%??  <br>
<br>
My government tells me that Iraq is a supporter and funder of terrorists - and has no intention of cleaning that up, so I agree, we should go after them.  Why do I agree?  Because I am worried about terrorists attacking us again?  Of course...but there is no doubt some revenge in my thinking as well...and yes, I know that Iraq is not directly linked to the 9/11 attacks, but damn it, they were dancing in the streets after it happened!  They must be involved somehow right? There is the revenge mentality in full effect, I think.<br>
<br>
Make no mistake, I still agree with the decision to go into Iraq.  I am putting some trust in my government to do the right thing.  Listening to many of you though, has helped me remember that I need to not only think with my heart, but with my head...<br>
<br>
Hopefully, I didn't sway too far off topic...  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :eek --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/eek.gif ALT=":eek"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
